observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE require the Local Finance Committee to:
Strictly comply with Item 2.6(a), Chapter 2, Part II of the BOM for LGUs in the determination of funds available for supplemental budgets;
Submit all the requirements listed under the “Audit Requirement/s” in the three tables presented above for validation in audit.

We recommended that the LCE require the MA and MT to:

(1) submit any of the following for all payments to local farmers: (a) certification that the farmer is in the RSBSA; (b) RSBSA identification card; or (c) Barangay Certification that the supplier is a bonafide farmer; 

(2) process and approve CAs only for those expenses which are allowed to be paid through CA in accordance with Sections 2.2, 3.1 and 3.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002; 

(3) strictly comply with Sections 6.2 and 6.4 of GPPB Circular 01-2020; and 

(4) strictly comply with the approved maximum accountability of the MT as Disbursing Officer amounting to ₱1.00 million in accordance with the approved Fidelity Bond.

We recommended that the LCE require: 

(a) all concerned officials and employees to liquidate their outstanding cash advances as of December 31, 2020; 

(b) the Municipal Accountant to: (1) submit to COA the status on the action taken by the LGU to the unliquidated cash advances of those separated from service, deceased and also those of the un-identified accountable officers totaling ₱97,263; and (2) send demand letters to those employees who are active in service with unliquidated cash advances totaling ₱165,422; 

(c) We further recommend that the LCE request formally for authority to write-off dormant unliquidated CAs aging 10 years and more totaling ₱68,839 and submit the same to COA Audit Team Leader and/or Supervising Auditor.  In this connection, we recommend that the LCE direct the MA to prepare an aging of unliquidated CAs to support the request for write-off, indicating in the remarks column the existence of the applicable conditions as indicated on Section 7.4 of COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; and (d) all concerned officials and employees of the strict compliance with Sections 4.1.2, 4.1.3 and 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 197-002.

We recommended that the LCE require the MA and MT to:
submit any of the following for all payments to local farmers: (a) certification that the farmer is in the RSBSA; (b) RSBSA identification card; or (c) Barangay Certification that the supplier is a bonafide farmer;
process and approve CAs only for those expenses which are allowed to be paid through CA in accordance with Sections 2.2, 3.1 and 3.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002;
comply strictly with Sections  6.2 and 6.4 of GPPB Circular 01-2020; and
adhere strictly with the approved maximum accountability of the MT as Disbursing Officer amounting to ₱1.00 million in accordance with the approved Fidelity Bond.

We recommended that the LCE require:
the MSWDO and other LGU personnel in-charge in the distribution of grocery packs and whole dressed chicken to submit the:
report, together with supporting documents on the unaccounted 152 grocery packs and 182 whole dressed chicken;
duly acknowledged list of beneficiary-families for the whole dressed chicken allocated to MDRRMO (10 pieces), MSWDO (15 pieces), MAO (two pieces) and Mayor’s Office (25 pieces);
acknowledgement receipt of named beneficiaries of the distributed 594 grocery packs and 714 whole dressed chicken previously claimed by others persons; and
all concerned personnel to comply strictly with Items 3.5 and 5.0 of LBC No. 125; the sufficiency and relevant documentation required under COA Circular No. 2012-001 and LGU’s internal agreement on the distribution of relief assistance.

We recommended that Management:

a.\tStrictly enforce the settlement of all unliquidated CAs as of December 31, 2019; 

b.\tStop the granting of additional CAs to accountable officers, officials and employees unless the previous ones are fully settled, to avoid accumulation of the same;

c.\tPrepare final demand letters for settlement of unliquidated CAs and send these to personnel already separated from service based on their last known addresses.  Also, determine if there are outstanding claims or other moneys due them from the LGU and apply the unliquidated CAs upon actual payments of claims; and

d.\tOtherwise, require the MA to initiate request for write-off of the dormant accounts in accordance with pertinent provisions of COA Circular 97-001 dated February 5, 2015.  The request shall be supported with documents required under the unnumbered memorandum dated July 21, 2014 of the Director IV, COA Regional Office No. V, Legaspi City.

We recommended that the LGU:
Submit notarized copy of MOA with signature of all concerned signatories;
Submit copy of Designation of Authorized Person for the project implementation. The position and designation of names of persons whose signatures appeared in the transaction;

The BAC to explain the discrepancy in the mode of procurement – as stated in the MOA and in the Purchase Order, likewise, the delivery period of one hundred days in one contract and August 17, 2015 in the other contract which covered the same transaction;

Submit authority of Mr. Neal Pastor Boragay as signatory to the Purchase Request, and as person who received the goods delivered to the LGU; and

Compute the penalty for late delivery of 54 units pedicab covered by delivery receipt dated September 18, 2015 for 31 days.

We  recommended that the LGU:
Submit notarized copy of Memorandum of Agreement with signature of all concerned signatories;

Submit copy of Designation of Authorized Person for the project implementation. The position and designation of names of persons whose signatures appeared in the transaction;

The BAC to explain the discrepancy in the mode of procurement – as stated in the Contract of Agreement and in the Purchase Order, likewise, the delivery period of one hundred days in one contract and August 17, 2015 in the other contract which covered the  same transaction;

Submit authority of Mr. Neal Pastor Boragay as signatory to the Purchase Request, and as person who received the goods delivered to the LGU; and

Compute the penalty for late delivery of 54 units pedicab covered by delivery receipt dated September 18, 2015 for 31 days.

We recommended that Management:
Strictly enforce the settlement of all unliquidated cash advances as of December 31, 2019;
Stop granting additional cash advances to accountable Officers, officials and employees unless the previous ones are fully settled, to avoid accumulation of the same;
Prepare final demand letters for settlement of unliquidated cash advances and send these to personnel already separated from service based on their last known addresses.  Also, determine if there are outstanding claims or other moneys due them from the LGU and apply the unliquidated cash advances upon actual payments of claims; and
Otherwise, require the Municipal Accountant to initiate request for write-off of dormant accounts in accordance with pertinent provisions of COA Circular 97-001 dated February 5, 2015.  The request shall be supported with documents required under the unnumbered memorandum dated July 21, 2014 of the Director IV, COA Regional Office No. V, Legaspi City.

We  recommended that the LGU:
Submit notarized copy of Memorandum of Agreement with signature of all concerned signatories;

Submit copy of Designation of Authorized Person for the project implementation. The position and designation of names of persons whose signatures appeared in the transaction;

The BAC to explain the discrepancy in the mode of procurement – as stated in the Contract of Agreement and in the Purchase Order, likewise, the delivery period of one hundred days in one contract and August 17, 2015 in the other contract which covered the  same transaction;

Submit authority of Mr. Neal Pastor Boragay as signatory to the Purchase Request, and as person who received the goods delivered to the LGU; and

Compute the penalty for late delivery of 54 units pedicab covered by delivery receipt dated September 18, 2015 for 31 days.

We recommended that:

The Municipal Treasurer’s Office submit to Accounting Office all the disbursements vouchers for cash advances, and the liquidation documents  on or before the  fifth day of the ensuing month, so as not to cause delay as the MOA provides for the immediate implementation of the SF program without unreasonable delay upon receipt of the fund;

The Municipal Accounting Office to check the completeness of entries on the Liquidation Reports and Official Receipts for the refund, and supporting documents submitted by the Accountable Officer, and to assign reference/JEV number in the posting of transactions in the Journal of Cash Disbursements. Strictly comply with the timetable on the submission of accounts as required under existing laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended that:
the Municipal Treasurer submits to Accounting Office all the disbursements vouchers, official receipts including the corresponding reports of each month on or before the fifth day of the ensuing month;
the Municipal Accountant strictly complies with the timetable on the submission of accounts as required under existing laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended that:
the Municipal Treasurer submits to Accounting Office all the disbursements vouchers, official receipts including the corresponding reports of each month on or before the fifth day of the ensuing month;
the Municipal Accountant strictly complies with the timetable on the submission of accounts as required under existing laws, rules and regulations.
